body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Here are two dual port RAM implementations, one using the same clock for both ports, one using separate clocks.

```
module dpram_singleclock
#(parameter DATA_WIDTH=8, parameter ADDR_WIDTH=6)
(
	input [(DATA_WIDTH-1):0] data_a, data_b,
	input [(ADDR_WIDTH-1):0] addr_a, addr_b,
	input we_a, we_b, clk,
	output reg [(DATA_WIDTH-1):0] q_a, q_b
);

	reg [DATA_WIDTH-1:0] ram[2**ADDR_WIDTH-1:0];

	// Port A 
	always @ (posedge clk)
	begin
		if (we_a) 
			ram[addr_a] <= data_a;
		else 
			q_a <= ram[addr_a];
	end 

	// Port B 
	always @ (posedge clk)
	begin
		if (we_b) 
			ram[addr_b] <= data_b;
		else 
			q_b <= ram[addr_b];
	end

endmodule

module dpram_dualclock
#(parameter DATA_WIDTH=8, parameter ADDR_WIDTH=6)
(
	input [(DATA_WIDTH-1):0] data_a, data_b,
	input [(ADDR_WIDTH-1):0] addr_a, addr_b,
	input we_a, we_b, clk, clk_b,
	output reg [(DATA_WIDTH-1):0] q_a, q_b
);

	reg [DATA_WIDTH-1:0] ram[2**ADDR_WIDTH-1:0];

	// Port A 
	always @ (posedge clk)
	begin
		if (we_a) 
			ram[addr_a] <= data_a;
		else 
			q_a <= ram[addr_a];
	end 

	// Port B 
	always @ (posedge clk_b)
	begin
		if (we_b) 
			ram[addr_b] <= data_b;
		else 
			q_b <= ram[addr_b];
	end

endmodule
```

```synth_ecp5 -top dpram_dualclock``` results in a DP16KD RAM block being inferred, whereas ```synth_ecp5 -top dpram_singleclock``` builds the RAM from logic cells instead.

Further, using the dualclock variant in a larger design which feeds both clk and clk_b from the same clock also causes the RAM to be built from logic rather than a RAM block.

## Expected behavior

I would expect a RAM block to be inferred whether or not the clock pins are fed from the same clock.

## Actual behavior

RAM block is inferred only if the two ports are fed from different clocks.

